title: For Sale:  DELUXE 1873 WINCHESTER 44-40 w/ "PERIOD CASE" NR
postcontent: Winchester Deluxe Model 1873 sporting rifle chambered in a 44 W.C.F. (44-40) caliber. The rifle itself comes with five special order features. (1) early style checkered stocks, (2) XXX grade fancy walnut, (3) case hardened receiver, (4) 26" octagon barrel (24" was standard), and (5) a Set trigger. This gun, serial number 57266 is an early 2nd Model, being manufactured in 1880 and comes with an emailed confirmation taken from the Winchester factory ledgers housed at the Cody Firearms Museum (see pic.#9). First Model 1873's were manufactured from serial number 1 to around 30,000 serial number, Second Model's were from 30,000 to 90,000, and 3rd Model's went from 90,000 to end of production (720,610). A Straight Grip Deluxe Model is much rarer than a Deluxe Model 1873 with a pistol grip stock. This Deluxe Model 1873 with a 3X grade walnut, a set trigger and an longer than standard barrel is a rare enough find. Added to that, this one comes with a "one of a kind" and very unique, hand made case from the period, shaped like the Model 1873. The case has been hand carved from a solid piece of wood to fit this 26" Deluxe like a glove. It is an amazing accessory that draws the most attention on my display table at guns shows. It has all original and period correct hardware, nothing has been replaced. Pictures do not do it justice, I guarantee you will love this case. It is quite valuable on its own. As for condition of the case, it is in near perfect condition, with minor wear to the handle and exterior finish. As for the rifle, another very rare feature is the courser, early style checkering.

title: For Sale:  EXCEPTIONAL" WINCHESTER 1876 DELUXE HIGH COND. NR
postcontent: Winchester Model 1876 Deluxe sporting rifle chambered in the 40-60 caliber. This rifle, serial #53011 was manufactured in 1886, has six special order features and comes with a letter taken from the factory ledgers housed at the Cody Firearms Museum showing its original configuration (see pics.#7 & 8). With the Model 1876 already having a low production of 63,871 guns, there were only 9,132 rifles manufactured in the 40-60. The 40-60 caliber had the fewest number of Deluxe guns made with only 268. The 50-95 Express rifles had the lowest production numbers of 3,281, but had 539 Deluxe models manufactured. The 45-75 had 16,617 rifles, with 802 Deluxe guns and the 45-60 had 24,176 rifles with 530 being Deluxe models. The other extremely rare features are that only a total of 76 rifles were manufactured with a 28" half octagon/half round barrel (which many of those would have had full magazines). Shotgun butt stocks totaled 139, half magazines numbered 198 and casehardened guns saw a total of 597. Combine all of these features on one gun and it would be safe to say that less than a handful of 1876's were manufactured in this configuration, which one or more surely was ordered by Teddy Roosevelt himself. Being a Deluxe gun with special order features, the rifle was hand-fitted by workmen who applied assembly numbers to aid in the final assembly after finish. I carefully removed the buttstock to find the matching assembly numbers of "2525" stamped on the lower left tang of the receiver and on the inlet of the stock (see pics#114 thru 117).

postcontent: Up for sale is brand new in case never fired HK VP9 Semi-automatic 9MM 4.09" Polymer Black 15Rd 2 Mags Fired Case M700009-A5Call or text Joe @ (602) 3 six one 7 2 seven 3 or email REDACTEDHECKLER & KOCH - VP9 - PISTOL - CALIBER: 9mm - STRIKER FIRED - BROWNING RECOIL OPERATED - TRIGGER PULL: 5.4lbs - MAGAZINES: 2 - CAPACITY: 15 ROUND - SIGHT RADIUS: 6.38" - BARREL LENGTH: 4.09" - WEIGHT W/EMPTY MAG: 26.56oz. - WEIGHT LOADED: 32oz. - INTERCHANGEABLE GRIP PANELS - Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail In development for more than four years, the VP9 is Heckler & Koch’s latest handgun and the first striker fired HK since the renowned P7 series pistols were introduced in the 1980s. Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK “light pull” trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun. HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset. The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break. The VP9 uses HK’s ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable backstraps and six side panels— accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistol’s grip also instinctively position an operator’s hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip. Although influenced by other HK models, the VP9 has all the hallmarks of the latest, state-of-the-art handgun. All controls are completely ambidextrous. Slide releases are present on both sides of the frame and the magazine release can be easily activated by left- or right-handed shooters. A new feature is HK’s patented charging supports — simple components that are mounted on each side of the rear of the slide and provide better gripping leverage for racking the slide rearward. The charging supports speed reloading and make operating the VP9 easier for shooters with reduced hand strength. The VP pistols uses the proven P30 steel magazine; 15 and 10-round capacity available. The VP9 has an extended Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail molded into its polymer frame for mounting lights and accessories. The rail has been tested and certified to handle mounted accessories up to 5.6 ounces. The VP9’s proprietary captive flat recoil spring helps reduce the recoil forces effecting the operator and the handgun, improving shooter control during rapid firing and prolonging component service life. HK’s famous cold hammer forged barrel — made from cannon grade steel — ensures long service life. Similar HK barrels on 9 mm P30 models have fired more than 90,000 rounds in endurance tests in 2010. The polygonal bore profile, with no traditional lands-and-grooves rifling, contributes to longer service life as well as a slight increase in muzzle velocity.

title: For Sale:  300 Win Mag Dies and Brass
postcontent:
Rebarreling my 300 Win Mag and no longer need this equipment or brass. If you live in Toledo or nearby, we can meet face to face for cash only transaction. 
I think there are around 200 once fired cases. This is military once fired brass used by Army snipers who have recently started using the 300 win mag. Primers are lacquer sealed but not crimped. It has been cleaned and that is it. $35 per 50.

The Redding Competition Micrometer seater die is very nice and is definitely one of the best seater dies you could buy. The die quickly and easily adjusts seating depth in .001" increments and limits runout to .001" or less. The box doubles as a shell holder. Brownells has this die listed at $106.95  with s&h you're looking at about $116.00. Buy this one for $90 and step up your game.

The Forster Bushing bump neck sizer die is used after you have fire formed your brass. It sets the shoulder back a few thou and allows you to headspace off of the shoulder. It also neck sizes the case. In so doing, this die maximizes case life and controls neck tension. Forster has them listed for $121.00 +s&h presently. Again, one of the best resizing dies you could purchase. It's yours for $100.00

The Lee Ultimate Rifle 4 die set includes a full length resizing die, a neck sizing die, and dead length seater die, a factory crimp die, a shell holder, and a powder dipper. Lee lists their 300 Winchester Magnum Ultimate Rifle 4-Die Set for $65.00 +s&h. I will sell this set for $45.  

The case gauge is an LE Wilson adjustable case gauge. It allows you to set up your sizer die so that it sizes your cases just enough to chamber in your rifle. You stick an unsized case fired from your rifle into the case gauge and then adjust the gauge with an allen wrench (included) so the case head is flush with the lowest step on the gauge. In this way you can set up your sizing die so that the brass isn't stretched out excessively during firing. It's very simple and very useful. Sells for $33.99 at Brownells presently. Yours for $25.00

postcontent: DRT .380 Auto 85 Gr JHP Case500 round case (25 boxes of 20 rounds)$400 for the case plus the cost of shippingYou carry a 380 ACP pistol to maximize concealability. The DRT 380 85 grain ammo maximizes lethality in this small caliber. It is designed to work and function in the many 380 micro pistols made today. A non-lead projectile with a Hollow Point Flat Based (HPFB) design. It's OAL is 0.955” allowing it to function properly even though it is a hollow point. Due to velocity and pressure restraints, this bullet fragments into several pieces, penetrating 9-11” of gelatin. The jacket will stay intact and its petals will expand, with approximately 50% of the core fragmenting. This allows the bullet to penetrate deep enough to stop a threat and the fragmentation that does occur will cause wound cavities of 1-3” in diameter. The DRT 380 bullet will penetrate soft barriers like sheet rock, plywood, car doors, and some windshields.
